{{Use British English|date=October 2016}} {{Infobox flag | Name = Saint Lucia | Article = | Image = Flag of Saint Lucia.svg | Alt = Flag of Saint Lucia | Use = 111111 | Symbol = <!-- |Use="6-digit FIAV usage code" is required. --> | Proportion = 1:2 | Adoption = 1 March 1967 (last modified in 2002) | Design = A light blue field with the small golden triangle behind the large white-edged black isosceles triangle in the centre. | Designer = Dunstan St Omer | Image2 = Flag of the Governor-General of Saint Lucia.svg | Imagetext2 = Standard of the [[Governor-General of Saint Lucia]] | Alt2 = | Use2 = <!-- Required for |Symbol2 --> | Symbol2 = <!-- |Use2="6-digit FIAV usage code" is required. --> | Proportion2 = 1:2 | Adoption2 = 1979 | Design2 = | Designer2 = }}
The '''flag of Saint Lucia''' consists of a [[cerulean blue]] field charged with a yellow [[triangle]] in front of a white-edged black [[isosceles triangle]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Flag of Saint Lucia|url=http://www.govt.lc/stluciaflag|accessdate=February 28, 2017}}</ref> Adopted in 1967 to replace the British [[Blue Ensign]] [[Defacement (flag)|defaced]] with the arms of the colony, it has been the flag of [[Saint Lucia]] since the country became an [[West Indies Associated States|Associated State]] of the [[United Kingdom]] that year. Although the overall design of the flag has remained unchanged, specific aspects of it have been altered over the years.
==History== The French colonised Saint Lucia in 1635 and subsequently signed a treaty with the local indigenous population 45 years later in 1680.<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|title=St Lucia profile|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-latin-america-19833217|work=BBC News|publisher=BBC|date=October 18, 2012|accessdate=September 26, 2014}}</ref> However, the British vied for control with the French, and the island frequently switched hands between the two powers.<ref name=LP>{{cite web|title=History of St Lucia|url=http://www.lonelyplanet.com/st-lucia/history|date=|accessdate=September 26, 2014|publisher=Lonely Planet}}</ref> This continued until 1814, when the [[Treaty of Paris (1814)|Treaty of Paris]] was signed that saw France permanently relinquish Saint Lucia to the British,<ref name=LP/> and it became a [[crown colony]] of the [[United Kingdom]] within [[British Empire|its colonial empire]] in that same year.<ref name=BBC/> During this colonial period of French and British rule, Saint Lucia did not have its own [[National flag|unique colonial flag]].<ref name=EB>{{cite encyclopedia|first=Whitney|last=Smith|encyclopedia=Encyclopædia Britannica|title=Flag of Saint Lucia|url=http://global.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1355481/flag-of-Saint-Lucia|date=June 26, 2014|accessdate=September 26, 2014|publisher=Encyclopædia Britannica, Inc.}} {{subscription required}}</ref>
The British finally granted Saint Lucia its own unique [[Coat of arms of Saint Lucia|coat of arms]] in August 1939. The [[Escutcheon (heraldry)|escutcheon]] consisted of a black shield featuring two sticks of bamboo forming a cross, with two [[Tudor rose]]s symbolising [[England]] and two [[Fleur-de-lis|fleurs-de-lis]] symbolising [[France]] occupying the four quadrants. This emblem was utilised to [[Defacement (flag)|deface]] the British [[Blue Ensign]] in order to form the territory's flag.<ref name=EB/>
The island became part of the [[West Indies Federation]] from 1958 to 1962.<ref name=BBC/> However, this political union turned out to be unsuccessful, and on 1 March 1967 – five years after the federation was dissolved – Saint Lucia became an [[West Indies Associated States|Associated State]].<ref name=EB/> This gave the territory full control over domestic matters, while Britain retained responsibility for the island's [[Foreign policy|foreign affairs]] and [[National security|defence]].<ref name=BBC/> The territory's new flag, which was designed by native Saint Lucian artist [[Dunstan St Omer]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WHZ25JlDrjYC&pg=PA96e|title=Saint Lucia|publisher=Marshall Cavendish|year=2008|last=Orr|first=Tamra|page=96}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=St Lucia: Michelangelo of the Caribbean|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/centralamericaandcaribbean/saintlucia/722278/St-Lucia-Michelangelo-of-the-Caribbean.html|date=February 12, 2000|first=Richard|last=Newton|accessdate=October 1, 2014|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph}}</ref> was adopted on that same day.<ref name=complete>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1yahq8im86kC&pg=PA36|title=Complete Flags of the World|publisher=Penguin|date=6 January 2009|last=Kindersley Ltd.|first=Dorling|page=36}}</ref> When Saint Lucia became an independent country on 22 February 1979, the overall design of the flag from twelve years before remained unchanged,<ref name=complete/><ref>{{cite news|title=Island of St. Lucia fights independence from Britain|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=GthBAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LqoMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4781,2860925&dq=flag+of+saint+lucia&hl=en|date=February 21, 1979|page=23|accessdate=October 1, 2014|newspaper=The Telegraph-Herald|location=Dubuque, Iowa|agency=United Press International}}</ref> but the blue colour's shade and the triangles' sizes were modified marginally.<ref name=EB/> Despite the fact that the island already had its own distinct flag by the time it became a sovereign state, the [[Union Jack]] was still lowered for the final time at the official ceremony marking independence.<ref>{{cite news|title=Little Caribbean island goes it alone|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=JJ8yAAAAIBAJ&sjid=8OkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4407,1161536&dq=flag+of+saint+lucia&hl=en|date=February 22, 1979|page=2A|accessdate=October 1, 2014|newspaper=The Miami News|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>
==Design== [[File:The Pitons of St Lucia YORYM-TA0184.jpg|thumb|right|A 1903 image of the [[Pitons]], the two conical volcanic edifices that are stylised as the two central triangles of the flag.]] The colours and symbols of the flag carry cultural, political, and regional meanings. The blue epitomises the sky and the sea,<ref name=CIA>{{cite web|title=Saint Lucia|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/st.html|date=|accessdate=September 26, 2014|work=The World Factbook|publisher=CIA}}</ref> specifically the [[Atlantic Ocean]] and [[Caribbean Sea]] which encircle the country.<ref name=EB/> The black and white allude to the harmonious relationship between the [[Black people|black]] and [[White people|white]] races. The yellow symbolises the sunshine,<ref name=EB/> as well as prosperity.<ref name=CIA/> The triangles represent the [[Pitons]],<ref name=complete/> which are twin volcanic cones located in the southwest part of the island and unity;<ref name=EB/> [[Gros Piton]] and [[Petit Piton]] are a national symbol of Saint Lucia.<ref name=CIA/>
==Historical flags== {| border="2" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" style="margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse;" |- bgcolor="#efefef" ! width="110"|Flag!!width="100"|Duration!!width="250"|Use!!width="250"|Description |- | [[File:Flag of Saint Lucia (1875-1939).png|border|100px]] || 1875–1939 || Flag of the colony of [[Saint Lucia]] || |- | [[File:Flag of Saint Lucia (1939–1967).svg|border|100px]] || 1939–1967 || Flag of the colony of [[Saint Lucia]] || A British [[Blue Ensign]] [[Defacement (flag)|defaced]] with the arms of the colony. This consisted of a black shield featuring two sticks of bamboo forming a cross, with two [[Tudor rose]]s symbolising [[England]] and two [[Fleur-de-lis|fleurs-de-lis]] symbolising [[France]] occupying the four quadrants. |- | [[File:Flag of Saint Lucia (1967–1979).svg|border|100px]] || 1967–1979 || Flag of Saint Lucia || A cerulean blue field charged with a yellow triangle in front of a white-edged black arrowhead. |- | [[File:Flag of Saint Lucia (1979-2002).svg|border|100px]] || 1979–2002 || Flag of Saint Lucia || A cerulean blue field charged with a yellow triangle in front of a white-edged black arrowhead. The yellow triangle was enlarged and the arrowhead made narrower. |}
