{{chart/end}}

The connection between these languages was first reported in linguistic literature by [[Johann Anton Güldenstädt]] in his 1773 classification of the languages of the Caucasus, and later proven by [[G. Rosen]], [[Marie-Félicité Brosset]], [[Franz Bopp]] and others during the 1840s. [[Zan languages|Zan]] is the branch that contains the [[Mingrelian language|Mingrelian]] and [[Laz language|Laz]] languages.

On the basis of [[glottochronology|glottochronological analysis]], [[Georgi Klimov]] dates the split of the [[Proto-Kartvelian language|Proto-Kartvelian]] into [[Svan language|Svan]] and [[Proto-Karto-Zan language|Proto-Karto-Zan]] to the 19th century BC,<ref name="Kli98b"/><ref name="Kli94">Klimov (1994), p. 91</ref> and the further division into [[Georgian language|Georgian]] and [[Zan languages|Zan]] to the 8th century BC,<ref name="Kli94">Klimov (1994), p. 91</ref> although with the reservation that such dating is very preliminary and substantial further study is required.<ref name="Kli98b"/>

The older name "South Caucasian" is no longer much used, as it derives from the idea that Kartvelian is related to the [[Northwest Caucasian]] and [[Northeast Caucasian]] languages, a position which is no longer maintained.

===Higher-level connections===
No relationship with other languages, including the two [[North Caucasian languages|North Caucasian language families]], has been demonstrated so far.<ref name=brit>[[Encyclopædia Britannica]], 15th edition (1986): [[Macropedia]], "Languages of the World", see section titled "Caucasian languages".</ref> Some linguists, such as [[Tamaz V. Gamkrelidze]], have proposed that the Kartvelian family is part of a much larger [[Nostratic languages|Nostratic]] language family, but both the concept of a Nostratic family and Georgian's relation to it are not considered likely by linguists.<ref>Allan R. Bomhard, John C. Kerns. (1994)'' The Nostratic Macrofamily: A Study in Distant Linguistic Relationship''.</ref>

Certain grammatical similarities with [[Basque language|Basque]], especially in the [[declension|case system]], have often been pointed out. However, the hypothesis of a relationship, which also tends to link the Caucasian languages with other non-Indo-European and non-Semitic languages of the Near East of ancient times, is generally considered to lack conclusive evidence.<ref name=brit/> Any similarities to other linguistic phyla may be due to [[Areal feature|areal]] influences. Heavy borrowing in both directions (i.e. from North Caucasian to Kartvelian and vice versa) has been observed; therefore it is likely that certain grammatical features have been influenced as well. If the [[Dené–Caucasian languages|Dené–Caucasian]] hypothesis, which attempts to link [[Basque language|Basque]], [[Burushaski]], the [[North Caucasian languages|North Caucasian families]] and other phyla, is correct, then the similarities to Basque may also be due to these influences, however indirect. Certain Kartvelian–[[Indo-European languages|Indo-European]] lexical links are revealed at the protolanguage level,<ref>Gamkrelidze & Ivanov (1995), pp. 774–776</ref> which are ascribed to the early contacts between [[Proto-Kartvelian language|Proto-Kartvelian]] and [[Proto-Indo-European language|Proto-Indo-European]] populations.<ref>Gamkrelidze & Ivanov (1995), p. 768</ref>

